es:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"More","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: nickname for a dark-skinned man, from a diminutive of Old French <i>more</i> ‘Moor’ (see   More  )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas De More was born in 1400, in More, Shropshire, England, his father, Thomas De More, was 47 and his mother, Matilda Fauconer, was 51. He married Joan about 1419, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died after 1430, in his hometown."},"et":{"1400–after 1430":"1400–pärast 1430","1400–1430":"1400–1430","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1426–Male":"1426–Surnud","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","about 1419":"umbes 1419","1426":"1426","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1353":"1353","1430":"1430","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1350":"1350","about 1399":"umbes 1399","after 1430":"pär